Alright, listen up, 'cause this is important for any time ya gotta make a deal with someone who ain't exactly from around the block. See, culture, it ain't just some fancy word, it's like the air you breathe, it shapes how ya think, how ya talk, how ya even eat your tacos. Each group's got its own flavor, its own way of doin' things, and you gotta respect that.

Thinkin' all Russians are stubborn or all Japanese are super chill? Nah, that's just plain wrong. It's like sayin' all cats are lazy just 'cause you met one who was snoozin' in a sunbeam.  Ya gotta dig deeper and figure out what makes that culture tick, how they see the world, 'cause that's gonna affect how they bargain.

When you're dealin' with folks from a different world, ya gotta remember, you see things through your own lens, ya know?  It's like lookin' at a picture through a funhouse mirror, things are a bit warped. So, instead of judgin' or tryin' to change 'em, just accept 'em for who they are, like a weird but cool uncle at a family reunion.  And especially if you're the one with less muscle at the table, ya gotta play nice.

Culture ain't just about countries, either. Even within a company, there's different vibes. Some places are all about grindin' 24/7, others are more laid-back.  You can tell by how folks dress, how they talk, even who gets the fancy corner office.

Values, those are the real deal, they're the "why" behind a culture. If a place values respect and harmony, they ain't gonna pull any dirty tricks to win a deal. And if they're all about gettin' the best bang for their buck, they ain't gonna back down easy.

So, before you even show up to the negotiation, do your homework. Learn about the other side, their customs, their values, their quirks. And hey, maybe even find out what their favorite pizza topping is. You never know, a little common ground can go a long way.

"A dumb dude once said, 'There ain't no God!'" That's what Psalm 14 in the Bible says, and it's where St. Anselm starts talkin' about how God exists. Seems like Thomas Aquinas, another brainy dude we're gonna check out, agrees with that.  

Now, they both think God is real, but we gotta stick to the same God they're talkin' about - the one from the Bible. If we start messin' around with different Gods,  it's like comparing apples and oranges. We gotta see which argument for *this* God is stronger.

Look, both Anselm and Aquinas make some good points, but neither one really lays out a totally rock-solid reason to believe in God.  

Let's break down Anselm first. He says we can find God by lookin' inside ourselves. He's sayin' that because God exists in our minds, we can't even imagine him not bein' real. It's kinda like sayin' that because you know somethin' exists in your head, it must be real. He's sayin' faith is enough, we don't need proof. 

Now, Thomas Aquinas is all about logic and proof, no faith needed. He's got five big arguments for God, sayin' that lookin' at the world around us shows us God's gotta be there. He's like, "Look at all this stuff, it couldn't just happen by chance, there's gotta be a reason!"

A long time ago, way back in the 500s BC, a prince was born who would later become known as Buddha. He decided to ditch all the fancy stuff of being a prince and became super wise. His teachings about life and stuff started something called Buddhism. There are lots of different types of Buddhism, but the oldest one is called Theravada. It's been around for more than 2,500 years, and it's changed a lot since Buddha's time.

For example, in Sri Lanka, a place where Theravada Buddhism is really big, they do this cool water-cutting ceremony every year. Monks and regular folks all join in, and it's pretty important to them even though Buddha never said anything about it. This shows how Buddhism has changed, from little things like ceremonies to really big ideas about what it means to be Buddhist.

Over time, both monks and regular people who practice Theravada Buddhism have had to change how they understand the religion. This happened because of stuff happening inside and outside of Buddhism. Sometimes it was good stuff, sometimes it was bad. 

We're gonna use some special words a lot: "internal" means something from inside Buddhism, like decisions made by Buddhist people, whether they're monks or not. "External" means something from outside Buddhism, like stuff from other religions or cultures. "Hostile" means something that wants to hurt Buddhism, and "benign" means something that doesn't care about helping or hurting Buddhism, but might end up doing one or the other by accident.

First, let's talk about the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in finding peace and happiness by following the "Triple Gem": the Buddha himself, his teachings (called the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (called the Sangha). The Dhamma is like a big library of Buddhist writings. It has three main parts: the Suttas (Buddha's talks), the Vinaya (rules for monks), and the Abhidhamma (deep philosophical stuff).  

A lot of Buddhist ideas are based on these things: Anatta (no permanent soul), Dukkha (life is full of suffering), and Anicca (everything is always changing). Buddhists believe that by understanding these things, they can escape the cycle of death and rebirth called Sansara. They also try to let go of desire, anger, and confusion (lobha, dosa, moha) so they can reach enlightenment. The Vinaya tells monks how to live their lives, with lots of rules for being good and ethical.  

The most important thing in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. The first is that life is full of suffering (Dukkha). The second is that suffering comes from clinging to things (attachment). The third is that suffering can end. The fourth is that there's a path to end suffering (The Eightfold Path).

So, get this, America and Mexico, they had this huge beef going on for like, 57 years.  It all started back in 1836 and went on till 1893. These guys were always at each other's throats! The worst part was this thing called the Mexican-American War, where America basically jumped Mexico. They won, of course, and took Texas and a bunch of land in the Southwest. Talk about a power move!

There were tons of other skirmishes between them, but things finally cooled down right before World War I. You see, they just couldn't see eye to eye on stuff like religion, culture, and who got what. It's like when your siblings fight over the TV remote, but on a whole other level.

This whole thing reminds me of other neighborly feuds, ya know? Countries that share a border tend to butt heads over stuff. It's like, you're both trying to claim the same parking spot, only with countries and land. 

One guy, David, said that America only really had major problems with Mexico and Cuba. These two countries, being right next door, were always causing trouble. Meanwhile, other Latin American countries were chillin' with the US.

Religion was a big deal too. Back then, America was all about not being Catholic or monarchy, kinda like how they were against communism and fascism later on. It's all about what you believe, I guess.

This whole distrust thing went way back to the whole English and Spanish thing. They were never really cool with each other, so it spilled over into America and Mexico's relationship.

These two countries had a ton of disagreements, mostly about borders and stuff.  Bandits and outlaws would just cross back and forth, causing mayhem. Both sides had to put a stop to it with some serious muscle.

Eventually, things started to calm down because Mexico needed America's help, kinda like relying on a sibling for homework. And then, America shifted from wanting more land to wanting to control Mexico's economy.  That was the end of the big rivalry.

Fifteen years ago, bam! Life threw me a curveball. I got hit with this sickness outta nowhere, one I'd never even heard of. Talk about a shocker! I was a nurse back then,  a job I picked for the safety and security I craved ever since I was a kid. "You can always find work as a nurse, people always get sick, right?" That's what everyone told me growing up. So, even though my real dream was to be a scientist or maybe even a journalist, I ended up in scrubs. 

But there I was, 46 years old, single, and out of a job, thanks to this mysterious illness. Fifteen years of relying on Social Security Disability later, and let me tell you, I'm down to my last dime.  I scrape by, but every day feels like a fight to keep my head above water. My security, my safety, my self-esteem – it's all shaky ground. Nothing feels certain anymore. But here's the thing: I wouldn't have made it this far without my family and a few good friends.  Believe me, when life throws a real curveball, you realize just how much you need others.

Life's gonna throw curveballs, big and small, no matter how prepared you think you are. Sometimes, you just need a helping hand. I totally get the whole "don't rely on big government" thing.  Let's face it, the system's got more holes than a Swiss cheese. But instead of everyone hunkering down in their own fallout shelters,  wouldn't it be better if we started trusting each other again?  Learning to help each other out, to ask for help when we need it?

Sure, people talk about "rugged individualism" being what built this country. But the truth is, our ancestors didn't cross the Rockies alone. They relied on each other, on compassion, respect, and sharing what they had.

So, yeah, be prepared. I am. I've got my disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, even duct tape for the windows. I've got flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and a whole pantry of canned goods. If you've got the space and the know-how, grow your own food, learn to can it.  A wood stove's a good idea too, unless you're living in an apartment.

But here's the real takeaway: get to know your neighbors. You never know when you'll need them.

So, you're wondering how things like bugs and clams and stuff get so weird lookin', right? Like, why'd they evolve to look that way? And what stops 'em from just getting totally bonkers? Back in 1917, this guy D'Arcy Thompson was like, "Man, we're just scratching the surface of figuring out how to describe even the simplest living thing with math." And, guess what? It's still kinda true today!

But hey, lately folks have been trying to use math to figure out how shells, those crazy coiled things, grow and change over time. Think of it like this: imagine a snail's shell is a tube that's constantly spinning around in a circle, like a super-slow tornado. Each twist of that tube is called a whorl, and they all spiral around a central point called the columella.

We can measure stuff like how big the whorls get and how fast they grow, and we can even use computers to make fake shells and see what's possible. We're using X-rays to get a good look at real shells, then we're plugging those measurements into this software called CerioShell. It's like building a digital toolbox for understanding how shells change over time.

We're combining all this with experiments and observations to try and understand how big changes happen in nature, like when a species evolves into something totally new. It's like solving a giant puzzle, piece by piece.

Yo, lemme tell ya about Indonesia's health scene, it's kinda messed up.  

See, for the last ten years, babies ain't been doin' so hot.  Sure, they're makin' progress on things like clean water and toilets, but when it comes to keepin' moms and kids healthy, they're way behind.  They gotta step it up if they wanna hit their goals by 2015. 

They're sayin' that more babies are bein' born with a doctor or midwife around, which is cool, but a lot of those midwives ain't qualified for emergencies.  So, even though they got more folks around, it ain't actually makin' things safer for moms.   

Plus, fewer kids are seein' doctors for tummy troubles, and they ain't trackin' how many folks are gettin' checkups after they have a baby.  That ain't a good sign.

They ain't doin' enough C-sections either, especially in the country.  In the city, it's 7%, but in the sticks, it's only 2%!  That means folks in the country ain't gettin' the same care. And the poor folks are havin' a real hard time gettin' to the doctor.  They can't afford it, ya know?

So, what's the deal?  Should they just focus on one specific problem or fix the whole health system?  Easy programs sound good, but they can suck the funding away from other important stuff.  Plus, you end up with a bunch of separate programs doin' the same thing, which is a headache and a waste of money.

So, like, Victorian books are all about being super detailed and, like, obsessed with rich people, ya know?  But then there are these two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," that are kinda different. They're still from that time period, but they're more mysterious and, like, kinda freaky, which is totally not what you'd expect.  It's kinda cool 'cause it makes the characters way more interesting. You get a better sense of what makes them tick, y'know?

Take this crazy passage from "Oliver Twist," for example: 

"And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 

(Dickens, 220)


It's like Oliver is having a totally messed-up dream, right? And these weird dreams and stuff are kinda common in both "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights." They help us understand what's going on inside the characters' heads, like what's hurting them and how they really feel about stuff.

In "Oliver Twist," these weird experiences often show us Oliver's inner turmoil.  When he remembers getting shot, it's like he's reliving it all over again in a dream. It's super intense, and it shows how scared and helpless he feels. He's totally overwhelmed, and it's like he can't even control what's happening to him. It makes you wonder who's really in charge of his life, because it sure ain't him. This whole shooting thing is super depressing, like Oliver is just giving up, ya know?

A couple years ago, lemme tell ya, I was workin' at this after-school thing, helpin' out little kids with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so that's what I mostly did. One lil' dude, Adrian, he was in third or fourth grade, I think, was really strugglin' with readin'. It was weird, like he knew some letters but others, forget about it! He spoke perfect English, mind you, but readin', it was a whole other story. He was Latino, I'm pretty sure, but that didn't seem to be the problem. We were stuck, until one day, Adrian's mom showed up. Now, she only spoke Spanish, and my Spanish was, well, let's just say it was more like broken Spanish. But somehow, we managed to talk. And then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read fine, he just didn't know the English alphabet that well! I don't know if it helped him much in the end, but I hope he's doin' better now.

I tell you this story 'cause it shows how tricky things can be with the language barrier in schools, especially here in California.  It ain't always as obvious as you'd think. Even for kids who speak English perfectly, readin' it can still be a real pain.  We all know this problem exists, so what can we do about it?  

For Adrian, it was pretty simple: some extra help with English readin', focusin' on the alphabet and sounds. But for kids who barely speak English, it's a whole different ballgame. There ain't no one-size-fits-all solution. Dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes - none of these things alone are gonna fix it. You gotta use a mix of everything!

First off, dual language programs are a great idea, not just for kids whose first language is Spanish, but for everyone.  Kids in those programs do better in school, you know? People get scared about it, thinkin' it's a waste of money and that most kids won't benefit. But that ain't true. If we made these programs the norm, not the exception, everyone would be better off. 

Now, how do we do that?  Do we make all teachers bilingual? That's a bit much, right?  But I think we should definitely have bilingual helpers, tutors, whatever you wanna call 'em.

Mack's latest robot was a pink bunny with a drum. Pathetic, I tell ya!  Kicked it once, battery popped right out.  Meanwhile, downstairs, some dude got back from filming a marshmallow commercial.  Before he could even get in the door, another guy decked him into a wall.  I bet he left a nice imprint.  Later, Camo and Katt, against his will, somehow got the high score on DDR Max 2.  Oh, and Gage just called.  He's got his dad's Hulk DVD, apparently.  Already saw it in theaters, though.  Ugh, what was I saying?  Oh, right!

Man, when I was a kid, everyone kept telling me there was somethin' bigger out there, somethin' I couldn't even imagine.  Some folks went to Sunday school, others to Temple, some even tried to find answers inside themselves.  Lotta people just took what their parents told 'em, no question asked.  But some of us, we said 'Nah, forget it!' There's nothin' out there but what I see in my own world.  We might start out valuing one thing, then bam!  Suddenly, we're all about somethin' else entirely.  Doesn't matter what path you choose, though.  We're all just trying to figure ourselves out, lookin' for some kinda light in the dark to guide us.  

Remember when my old man told me his favorite bird was a cardinal?  We were sittin' on the porch, rain beatin' down on that tin roof like crazy, both of us smokin' our cigarettes.  The gutters were overflowin', drownin' all the plants by the edge.  He was lookin' out at the rain, kinda lost in thought, like he was searchin' for somethin' or rememberin' somethin' else. He'd gotten thinner these past few months, clothes hangin' off him like a bad joke.  His hair was thinner too, not as full as I remembered.  He wouldn't look at me, just kept lookin' at that rain.  I felt all alone and scared, but couldn't bring myself to talk to him about missin' him.  Didn't wanna make it real for either of us.  So I just hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in starin' out at the rain.

My dad passed away in December that year, five days after my 22nd birthday.  Chemo and radiation kept him alive a few months longer than the doctors thought, but it didn't ease his pain.  I couldn't see the point of it all.  What kinda God would do that?  I didn't pray that night.  If there was a God, I thought, he stopped listenin' to me a long time ago.

Couldn't bear to watch him go, so I didn't.  Couldn't watch the life that made me end.  I wanted to remember him how he lived, not how he died.  Besides, I knew my dad better than anyone else, even his own family.  He wouldn't want me to be a spectator at his death.  I curled up in bed for three days straight, waitin' for the news.

No one even bothered to call.

Yo, lemme tell ya 'bout this thing called the "Gothic Novel." It's kinda like an oxymoron, ya know? Like, it's both old and new at the same time. This dude Ian Watt, he said that in his book, "The Rise of the Gothic Novel."

People have been talkin' 'bout Gothic novels for ages, sayin' they're either crap or masterpieces. Some say they ain't got no depth, others say they're full of this "terrible sublime" stuff.  

See, the first real Gothic novel was this thing called "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. He mixed up old-school theater stuff with this newfangled "nature writing" thing goin' on at the time. He called it a "Gothic Story," and it kinda blew everyone's minds. 

Gothic novels are all about lookin' back at that old medieval stuff—the castles, the theaters, the whole vibe. Even back then, the word "Gothic" was kinda like a catch-all for anything ancient or, like, uncool compared to the shiny new stuff everyone was into. 

The cool thing about Gothic is that it blends this dramatic, theatrical stuff with this new way of writing novels where you get inside the characters' heads, ya know? That's why it's stuck around for so long, even though it feels kinda outdated sometimes. 

One big thing in Gothic novels is chivalry.  Back in the day, chivalry was all about trainin' up a proper knight, right?  Well, Gothic writers were obsessed with chivalry 'cause it represented this ideal: brave, honorable, the whole deal. They thought society had kinda lost sight of that.

So, in Gothic novels, they use chivalry to romanticize the past and try to make the present a little better. This guy Walpole, who wrote "The Castle of Otranto," was livin' through some crazy political times. He was probably feelin' pretty down on the world and thought maybe folks back in the day were just better people. He uses chivalry to show that in his story.  

Take this character, Frederic, for example. From the get-go, he's described as this perfect knight: a prince, tragic, probably gonna be a hero.  It's all very dramatic, kinda like a superhero but with swords and stuff.

Alright, so picture this: you wanna get somethin', right? Like, somethin' super-duper awesome from the store.  Well, that's where the whole "supply chain" thing comes in. It's like a crazy, awesome rollercoaster ride for stuff, from the moment you say "I want that!" all the way to when it lands in your grubby little hands.

This whole idea came from this guy, Keith Oliver, back in '82. He was like, "Hey, let's get organized! We gotta make sure peeps get what they want, fast and without any drama!"  So he came up with this thing called "supply chain management," which is basically like a super-secret recipe for makin' sure stuff gets where it needs to go.

There are six key ingredients in this recipe: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information.  Think of it like buildin' a burger:  you gotta have the right ingredients, the right place to cook it, and a way to get it to the hungry customer!

First up is production. That's where the magic happens!  We gotta figure out what peeps want, how much to make, where to make it, and who's gonna make it. It's like, "Hey, customers love chocolate chip cookies, so let's bake a ton of those!" Then we gotta figure out where to bake them, what ovens to use, and when to start bakin'.

Next comes supply.  This is where we find the ingredients and the workers.  We gotta make sure we have enough flour, sugar, and chocolate chips, and that our bakers are ready to roll!  Sometimes, we even outsource stuff to other companies, like "Hey, you guys make awesome sprinkles, can you send us a whole truckload?"

Inventory is like the middleman. It's all about keeping track of how much stuff we have and making sure we don't run out of anything. We don't want anyone to be sad because we're all out of chocolate chips!

Location, location, location! This is where we decide where to bake those cookies, distribute them, and where customers can buy them.

Transportation is how we get those cookies from the oven to the store. We gotta figure out the fastest, cheapest, and safest way to get those delicious treats to hungry hands.

And finally, information is the glue that holds it all together. We gotta keep track of everything - what's being made, where it's going, and when it's arriving.

So, check this out, right? This chick, Ellen Page, the one from Juno, is standing on the corner with a sign. It says, "Hitler is alive in Burma!"  Crazy, huh? 

Now, Burma, also known as Myanmar, is this place ruled by some seriously messed-up guys. They took over back in 1962, and things haven't been good ever since. A few years back, like 2007, some monks, wearing these saffron robes, started protesting. They called it the "Saffron Revolution," get it? 

At first, the government was all, "Whatever, monks, chill out," but then things got outta hand.  People started joining in, and the government went totally bananas. They cracked down hard, beating monks, shutting down protests, and even locking up journalists. One guy, a photographer from Japan, got killed just for taking pictures! 

They say 13 people died, but some folks in the know say it was way more. Like, thousands. This kinda stuff, it's not new. Governments have always tried to squash anyone who dares to speak up against them.  

Remember the Romans? They thought they were gods, right? And the Japanese emperors? They're supposed to be gods too! And here in America, we got George W. Bush talking to Ted Haggard, the leader of, like, the dumbest people ever. 

There's Tiananmen Square in China, where the government went all crazy on students and protesters. And then there's Rwanda, where they just murdered tons of people because of their ethnicity. And, of course, Hitler and the Holocaust.  

It's never ending, you know? This whole fight for freedom and justice, it's a constant struggle.

Duke Ellington, man, he was a legend in the jazz world, ya know?  He stuck around forever, and that gave him tons of time to really make his orchestra his own. Sure, he wasn't always front and center on the piano in his tunes, but  this dude could write some seriously complex and cool stuff. 

He knew how to make a song where a guy could go crazy and improvise, but he also knew how to make tight, orchestrated sections that really highlighted what each musician brought to the table.  Like, he'd craft these sounds that were totally unique and made each piece pop.  He was a master at getting the best out of every player, and that's how he made some of the most awesome jazz ever.

They even say in that big music book, The Grove Music Dictionary, that Ellington was all about using the voice as an instrument, check out his song "Creole Love Call" for that. He was using voices for texture and feeling without all that singing stuff. And in that song, he showed how he could make soloists shine, which he did all the time.

It's a slow blues song, twelve bars, six choruses, each one different. The first chorus is call and response between the voice and the reeds, smooth at first then kinda rough by the end. Chorus two, it's a muted trumpet solo that messes with the melody and throws in some of those bluesy notes. Then chorus three is all clarinet, high and sweet, with the piano adding a little somethin' somethin' underneath. Chorus four is the whole band echoing the first chorus, brass and reeds doin' the call and response thing. Chorus five, this is where it gets wild, the reeds are callin' and respondin' high up, with the brass and rhythm guys doin' this syncopated stop time thing. And the last chorus is back to the first call and response, but this time the voice gets all growl-ey, soloin' like an instrument itself.

Then there's a little tag with the voice doin' some runs and the trombone endin' on this dissonant note, real weird.

Ellington used voice like that in a lot of his stuff, adding this extra layer of sound. 

His song "Hot and Bothered" is another example of how good he was at orchestrating things and finding those cool sounds. He had "Bubber" Miley on trumpet and Baby Cox scatting, and their voices and instruments blended together so well. Then in "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," he used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton on trombone to start the melody, and it sounded killer.

She'd always felt somethin' was missin'. It was like a hole in her soul, a yearning that just wouldn't quit. This emptiness started creepin' in around 14, right when she was hittin' that teenage groove. Three years later, at 17, it was still there, gnawin' at her. Now, she knew it wasn't some material thing she was after, it was somethin' more...someone. But guys? Forget about it. They'd try their cheesy pick-up lines and awkward dances, but nothin' ever clicked. She'd wrack her brain, tryin' to figure out why this was happenin' to her. Theories flew around, but nothin' stuck. So she just kept livin', always questionin', always searchin'.

Life at home was usually chill. Her folks were good people, peaceful and calm. They rarely argued, and even when she tried to push their buttons, it usually ended in a good-natured debate. Her parents were the picture of serenity, but she, well, she was a whirlwind of energy and fun. It was a good mix, made her pretty darn likeable.

But today? Today was nothin' like usual. She was wanderin' around the house, lookin' for some spark of inspiration, when she heard a yelp from the kitchen. It was her mom's voice, short and sharp. She bolted into the room, panic settin' in, "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?!"  Her mom was sprawled on the floor, lookin' pale and in pain. "Ow...sweetie...need...hospital," her mom gasped, each word a strained effort. "Okay Mom, just tell me where to meet you," she said, her voice shaky but determined. Her mom pointed weakly, and the daughter, thank goodness for those self-defense classes, scooped her up and carried her to the car.

The hospital was a sensory overload - disinfectant, sick smells, and a palpable fear in the air. But she barely noticed. All her energy was focused on gettin' her mom help. She practically flew through the doors, barkin' for a doctor. Concerned faces swarmed around them, a gurney appeared, and they whisked her mom away.  She sat there, waitin', worry gnawin' at her insides.

Turns out, her mom had been tryin' to reach a vase on a high shelf and took a tumble off the step stool.

Listen up, folks! This study was all about how good that Mediterranean Diet (the Med diet) is for your ticker.  They found that the more you stick to it, the less likely you are to get heart problems or have a stroke.  This fancy "aMed" diet is like the Med diet's cooler cousin, with more plants, good fats, and fish, and less of the meaty stuff and bad fats. Think of it like a healthy power-up for your heart!

There's already been some talk about how the Med diet is good for you, but this study focused on strokes and heart attacks specifically. They followed all these nurses for like 20 years and asked them about what they ate. The nurses were awesome and kept track of their meals for years and years. They even double-checked everything with doctors and records to make sure they were getting it right.

So, what did they find? Well, the nurses who ate more like they were on vacation in Greece had way less heart problems and strokes. It's like magic, but it's actually science! The more they ate those healthy foods, the better protected they were.

Whoa, dude, picture this: 2007, the USA goes totally bonkers. Like, everyone's outta work, houses are crashing harder than a video game rage quit, and all the big fancy companies are, like, totally toast. This whole mess is still hanging around, so we gotta figure out what went wrong, right?

So, get this, it all started with some politicians who were, let's just say, not thinking straight. They pushed banks and companies to give out these crazy loans to people who couldn't really afford 'em. It was like handing out candy to a bunch of sugar-crazed kids! And these loans, they weren't even good loans, they were like, "sub-prime" or whatever. 

Meanwhile, these two guys, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, were supposed to be keeping things safe, but they got pressured into bundling up these bad loans into these even weirder things called CDOs and CDSs. It was like a financial game of Jenga, but instead of blocks, they were using people's houses!

When folks started missing payments, BAM! The whole thing came crashing down. Banks ran outta cash, and everyone got dragged down with 'em. It was like a domino effect, except way scarier and with way more money involved. 

This whole mess started way back in 1999, when President Clinton was trying to win another term. He wanted to look good, so he relaxed the rules on lending. That was like pouring gasoline on a fire, except the fire was the economy.

Some smart guy named Steven Holmes even saw it coming back then. He wrote about how Fannie Mae was getting pressured to give out more loans, even though it was risky. He warned that it could lead to another big financial disaster, just like the one with the savings and loans back in the 80s. 

And guess what? He was right!  People started taking out loans they couldn't afford, and they got themselves caught up in all these complicated new types of mortgages. They were buying houses they couldn't really afford, and then they started building stuff on top of stuff, like a financial skyscraper made of wobbly blocks. It was insane!

Then, BOOM! The bubble burst. All those houses that were worth way too much suddenly weren't worth anything. The banks lost tons of money, and some of the biggest companies in the world almost went bankrupt.

It was a total mess. And it's still affecting us today.

Ugh, exposition. That part in your story where you're supposed to show off your writing skills, wowing everyone with your fancy words and captivating sentences. Or maybe the part where your readers yawn, close their tabs, and mutter curses under their breath. I've seen Dr. Merlin yell at her computer screen when she gets stuck in a giant info-dump, and it's not in a good way.

Exposition, my friends, is not your bestie.

You already know the golden rule of writing: "Show, don't tell." But even I, Dr. Merlin, stumble into those boring, wordy paragraphs where nothing happens, or worse, too much happens all at once. Exposition is that little voice whispering in your ear, urging you to get all the background info out of the way before the real fun begins.  (Don't confuse it with the other voice tempting you to spill every single detail about each character's childhood!)

Exposition means dumping a bunch of info on your audience, usually in plain, straightforward language. Think of those long winded scenes in movies where one character drones on and on, giving another character a history lesson, like some kind of real-life "Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In writing, it's the author doing the heavy lifting of the telling.

Let me give you an example. Imagine you're reading a story, and you're told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, they got hitched in a big fancy wedding, and then, bam! Her husband was murdered right in front of her eyes! Would you really want two whole pages dedicated to explaining all that, with the characters only getting two lines of dialogue each? 

Nah, you'd expect the author to give us a taste of the husband's character, showing us through his words and actions how much he loved his wife. You'd also want to see how the heroine changed and grew because of him, through big gestures and little details.

A good introduction to the husband would make you feel something for him, make you care about his fate. And when he's gone, you'd mourn with the heroine, connecting with her on a deeper level.

In short, you want substance, not just bare bones.

Think of it like this: "They met, they married, he died."  That's the bare minimum. As a writer, you need to give us the juicy details, the "meat on the bones."

Sometimes we're tempted to rush past important stuff. Maybe you have a new character who was in the Air Force, now works the night shift at a gas station, has been married twice, no kids, loves fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the station someday, and just had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Give us the good stuff!

Mack, why are we even watching the news? This stuff is so boring! The first story was about some dude named Shad Hostettler stabbing his wife in Ashley, Ohio.  Did they even show her face? Nope! Just a picture of Shad lookin' all evil. They said he stabbed her a bunch of times, but that's about it. 

Then they talked about some kid, Travis Buyers, getting shot in Sharon Woods. Sounds pretty rough, but they barely said anything.  It's like they don't care 'cause he's black.  Remember that time a white kid went missing? The whole news was obsessed! 

Next up, some weirdo shot a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter with a .22! They were offering five grand for info on the shooter, so maybe someone will spill the beans.

They gave a quick rundown about the weather, sayin' it's gonna be hot and stormy on Saturday.  Typical.

Then they talked about some dude robbing a UDF. They kept sayin' he was a "dark-skinned black man" wearing a hoodie. What's with all the emphasis on his race? Sounds like someone's trying to stir up some trouble.

Finally, they had a story about this drug kingpin from Texas named Rene Rodriguez.  They kept saying "300 months" instead of 25 years, like that's supposed to sound scarier.  And they mentioned he was Hispanic, which had nothing to do with the story. 

This news is so messed up, I'm outta here!

Brothers, man, they're a crazy bunch. You know how it is, right? It's like, this unbreakable connection, like they're lookin' at each other in the mirror, but seein' even deeper, ya know?  They feel everything together, the good stuff and the bad. Love, pride, jealousy, even that nasty stuff like anger and cruelty - it's all there.

They get each other like nobody else, and sometimes it gets messy. It's like, when things get rough, that bond just shines through, like a crazy light show. But man, it comes with a price, ya know? You gotta deal with all those emotions, the good and the bad. 

See, when you look your brother in the eye, you see yourself, but not how people see you, but like, the real you. It's all in your actions, what you do and the stuff that comes after. That's where you see your true colors, the real deal.

There's this story, "The Scarlet Ibis," about these two brothers, and they're goin' through all this, ya know? It's got this crazy landscape, like a jungle out there, and these two boys are on this trip that's not gonna end well. There's this fightin' going on inside of 'em, pride and disappointment, and it explodes in this big way. Only one brother makes it out alive. The story shows you how those feelings between brothers can be so intense, and the narrator, he's like, right there in the middle of it all, feelin' everything too. 

The main guy in the story, he's all about pride, ya know? From the start, when he and his little brother, Doodle, go out, he's already got this resentment. He wants a brother who can do all this stuff with him, run races, climb trees, be his buddy. But Doodle's got this heart problem, so he's weak and can't do any of that. Imagine that, your dreams crushed right before your eyes! It's messed up. He even thinks about hurting Doodle, can you believe that? But then Doodle smiles at him, and he's like, "Aw, forget it, I love this little guy."

So, get this. Our brains, they're like, totally crazy complex, right? Kinda like trying to figure out a super complicated video game. Back in the day, people thought our brains were like wax tablets or papyrus – kinda like old school notepads. Then they were all, "Nah, it's more like a book!" But now, everyone's like, "Dude, it's like a computer!"

But hold up, these comparisons, they're kinda limited, you know? Like, they can get you thinking some crazy stuff.

See, all this info comes flooding in through our senses. Our eyes see light, our ears hear sounds, our skin feels stuff, and so on. It's all turned into these electrical signals – like, the language of our brain.

And then the brain does this crazy thing. It processes this info, like, a million different ways. It starts with the basics – like, "Hey, there's a black thing on a white thing." Then it's like, "Wait, that black thing looks kinda like a box!" It uses what it already knows to figure stuff out faster. Kinda like using cheats in a game, you know?

But here's the thing – our brains are picky. They only pay attention to the important stuff. Like, you see a ton of grass when you look down, but you don't notice every single blade. But if someone says your name in a crowded room, BAM, you hear it loud and clear.

And then there's memory. Our brains are like, "Ooh, gotta store that!" There's short-term memory – like remembering your last pizza topping – and long-term memory – like remembering your first pet's name. They store stuff in different ways, kinda like different folders on a computer.

But how is all this knowledge organized? There are tons of theories about that, like, maybe it's like a giant web of connections, or maybe it's like a library with books on every topic.

The brain is seriously mind-blowing, man.

Yo, check it! Aldous Huxley's book, "Brave New World," is like, totally a warning about tech and money stuff runnin' wild.  He paints this messed-up future where everyone's all about being part of the crew and gettin' instant happiness, you know? It's like a big, messed up game where people are just pawns,  followin' the rules set by this dude, the World Controller. It's kinda like what Marx woulda said, you dig?  Huxley's got this lowkey suspicion about how these systems are gonna mess things up.  He uses words like "homogeny" and "reification," which are like,  big Communist vibes, to show how messed up it is.

Basically, Huxley's saying capitalism is a scam. They keep us blind to how the rich really get rich, 'cause we're all too busy chasin' our own little pleasures.  It's like brainwashing, man!  The World Controller's like the big boss, makin' everyone crave stuff they don't need.  He's got all the power, and the lower classes are just slaves to the system. They don't even know they're bein' controlled. They're like, "Yeah, this is great! More stuff!" 

And the relationships? Forget about it! There's no real connection between people. They're just empty shells, man.  Huxley's sayin' that technology and money are killin' our soul, makin' us shallow and heartless.  Love?  Emotions?  Nah, not in this world. It's all about lookin' good and havin' a good time, even if it's fake.  It's a total bummer, dude.

Yo, lemme tell ya, gettin' around this crazy place, University Park, is a real pain in the tailfeather! I've been here for like, two and a half years, four and a half semesters, and lemme tell ya, it's a jungle out there! My freshman year, they stuck me in East Halls, man, like, the farthest point east on campus.  Forget the stadium and that Bryce Jordan Center thing, they're still closer to civilization than that!

So, picture this: I gotta trek from my East Halls bunker all the way to Willard, which is like, smack dab in the middle of this campus, just to get to class. On foot, it'd take me 25 minutes, even longer if the weather decides to throw a tantrum, which, let's be real, it does all the time here in State College.

I was talkin' to this dude, a grad not much older than myself, and he spilled the beans:  used to be, East Halls was like, surrounded by a freakin' desert, all empty land. Now? Boom! Sports fields, massive buildings, even a new Creamery and a fancy new health center! And apartments everywhere! This campus keeps growing, but getting around? Getting worse, dude.

So, what's the answer to this mobility mess? Bikes, man! Bikes are the key! But wait, it ain't just about the bike itself. Students gotta ride 'em, and the damn campus needs to play nice with us cyclists.

I was hangin' out with my buddy, he got back on the bike after a few years off. Said he couldn't believe he ever stopped. "Bikes are awesome," he said, "it's like, the only way to get around." They're good for your body, too. Trust me, a bowl of oatmeal and a little pedal power, you'll be cruisin' 30 miles in no time.

Like, most of the students here, I live off campus now. Just as far from the center as some dorms. Best decision I made this year? Bought a bike. Now I got class in Thomas building, a good 25-minute walk from my place. Bike? Five minutes flat if I'm feelin' speedy!

But here's the catch: Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas, but it ain't always a bike-friendly street, you know? Walkin' ain't bad, but I'm too busy for that. No bike, I'm stuck walkin' to class every day. That's like, 30-40 minutes each way, man! Over two and a half hours every week! Forget about it! That's time I don't got.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that is designed to track an index, a commodity or a basket of assets like an index fund, but is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange.  An ETF gives you the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of single stock ownership like the ability to sell short, buy on margin and purchase as few as a one share in any transaction.  Though these benefits are extremely attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are far lower than those of the average mutual fund.  Unfortunately, there are some down sides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would pay on a stock order.  Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available.
