Before he could even get in the door, another guy decked him into a wall.  I bet he left a nice imprint.  Later, Camo and Katt, against his will, somehow got the high score on DDR Max 2.  Oh, and Gage just called.  He's got his dad's Hulk DVD, apparently.  Already saw it in theaters, though.  Ugh, what was I saying?  Oh, right!

Man, when I was a kid, everyone kept telling me there was somethin' bigger out there, somethin' I couldn't even imagine.  Some folks went to Sunday school, others to Temple, some even tried to find answers inside themselves.  Lotta people just took what their parents told 'em, no question asked.  But some of us, we said 'Nah, forget it!' There's nothin' out there but what I see in my own world.  We might start out valuing one thing, then bam!  Suddenly, we're all about somethin' else entirely.  Doesn't matter what path you choose, though.  We're all just trying to figure ourselves out, lookin' for some kinda light in the dark to guide us.  

Remember when my old man told me his favorite bird was a cardinal?  We were sittin' on the porch, rain beatin' down on that tin roof like crazy, both of us smokin' our cigarettes.  The gutters were overflowin', drownin' all the plants by the edge.  He was lookin' out at the rain, kinda lost in thought, like he was searchin' for somethin' or rememberin' somethin' else. He'd gotten thinner these past few months, clothes hangin' off him like a bad joke.  His hair was thinner too, not as full as I remembered.  He wouldn't look at me, just kept lookin' at that rain.  I felt all alone and scared, but couldn't bring myself to talk to him about missin' him.  Didn't wanna make it real for either of us.  So I just hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in starin' out at the rain.

My dad passed away in December that year, five days after my 22nd birthday.  Chemo and radiation kept him alive a few months longer than the doctors thought, but it didn't ease his pain.  I couldn't see the point of it all.  What kinda God would do that?  I didn't pray that night.  If there was a God, I thought, he stopped listenin' to me a long time ago.

Couldn't bear to watch him go, so I didn't.  Couldn't watch the life that made me end.  I wanted to remember him how he lived, not how he died.  Besides, I knew my dad better than anyone else, even his own family.  He wouldn't want me to be a spectator at his death.  I curled up in bed for three days straight, waitin' for the news.

No one even bothered to call.

Yo, lemme tell ya 'bout this thing called the "Gothic Novel." It's kinda like an oxymoron, ya know? Like, it's both old and new at the same time. This dude Ian Watt, he said that in his book, "The Rise of the Gothic Novel."

People have been talkin' 'bout Gothic novels for ages, sayin' they're either crap or masterpieces. Some say they ain't got no depth, others say they're full of this "terrible sublime" stuff.  

See, the first real Gothic novel was this thing called "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. He mixed up old-school theater stuff with this newfangled "nature writing" thing goin' on at the time. He called it a "Gothic Story," and it kinda blew everyone's minds. 

Gothic novels are all about lookin' back at that old medieval stuff—the castles, the theaters, the whole vibe. Even back then, the word "Gothic" was kinda like a catch-all for anything ancient or, like, uncool compared to the shiny new stuff everyone was into. 

The cool thing about Gothic is that it blends this dramatic, theatrical stuff with this new way of writing novels where you get inside the characters' heads, ya know? That's why it's stuck around for so long, even though it feels kinda outdated sometimes. 

One big thing in Gothic novels is chivalry.  Back in the day, chivalry was all about trainin' up a proper knight, right?  Well, Gothic writers were obsessed with chivalry 'cause it represented this ideal: brave, honorable, the whole deal. They thought society had kinda lost sight of that.

So, in Gothic novels, they use chivalry to romanticize the past and try to make the present a little better. This guy Walpole, who wrote "The Castle of Otranto," was livin' through some crazy political times. He was probably feelin' pretty down on the world and thought maybe folks back in the day were just better people. He uses chivalry to show that in his story.  

Take this character, Frederic, for example. From the get-go, he's described as this perfect knight: a prince, tragic, probably gonna be a hero.  It's all very dramatic, kinda like a superhero but with swords and stuff.

Alright, so picture this: you wanna get somethin', right? Like, somethin' super-duper awesome from the store.  Well, that's where the whole "supply chain" thing comes in. It's like a crazy, awesome rollercoaster ride for stuff, from the moment you say "I want that!" all the way to when it lands in your grubby little hands.

This whole idea came from this guy, Keith Oliver, back in '82. He was like, "Hey, let's get organized! We gotta make sure peeps get what they want, fast and without any drama!"  So he came up with this thing called "supply chain management," which is basically like a super-secret recipe for makin' sure stuff gets where it needs to go.

There are six key ingredients in this recipe: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information.  Think of it like buildin' a burger:  you gotta have the right ingredients, the right place to cook it, and a way to get it to the hungry customer!

First up is production. That's where the magic happens!  We gotta figure out what peeps want, how much to make, where to make it, and who's gonna make it. It's like, "Hey, customers love chocolate chip cookies, so let's bake a ton of those!" Then we gotta figure out where to bake them, what ovens to use, and when to start bakin'.

Next comes supply.  This is where we find the ingredients and the workers.  We gotta make sure we have enough flour, sugar, and chocolate chips, and that our bakers are ready to roll!  Sometimes, we even outsource stuff to other companies, like "Hey, you guys make awesome sprinkles, can you send us a whole truckload?"

Inventory is like the middleman. It's all about keeping track of how much stuff we have and making sure we don't run out of anything. We don't want anyone to be sad because we're all out of chocolate chips!

Location, location, location! This is where we decide where to bake those cookies, distribute them, and where customers can buy them.

Transportation is how we get those cookies from the oven to the store. We gotta figure out the fastest, cheapest, and safest way to get those delicious treats to hungry hands.

And finally, information is the glue that holds it all together. We gotta keep track of everything - what's being made, where it's going, and when it's arriving.

So, check this out, right? This chick, Ellen Page, the one from Juno, is standing on the corner with a sign. It says, "Hitler is alive in Burma!"  Crazy, huh? 

Now, Burma, also known as Myanmar, is this place ruled by some seriously messed-up guys. They took over back in 1962, and things haven't been good ever since. A few years back, like 2007, some monks, wearing these saffron robes, started protesting. They called it the "Saffron Revolution," get it? 

At first, the government was all, "Whatever, monks, chill out," but then things got outta hand.  People started joining in, and the government went totally bananas. They cracked down hard, beating monks, shutting down protests, and even locking up journalists. One guy, a photographer from Japan, got killed just for taking pictures! 

They say 13 people died, but some folks in the know say it was way more. Like, thousands. This kinda stuff, it's not new. Governments have always tried to squash anyone who dares to speak up against them.  

Remember the Romans? They thought they were gods, right? And the Japanese emperors? They're supposed to be gods too! And here in America, we got George W. Bush talking to Ted Haggard, the leader of, like, the dumbest people ever. 

There's Tiananmen Square in China, where the government went all crazy on students and protesters. And then there's Rwanda, where they just murdered tons of people because of their ethnicity. And, of course, Hitler and the Holocaust.  

It's never ending, you know? This whole fight for freedom and justice, it's a constant struggle.

Duke Ellington, man, he was a legend in the jazz world, ya know?  He stuck around forever, and that gave him tons of time to really make his orchestra his own. Sure, he wasn't always front and center on the piano in his tunes, but  this dude could write some seriously complex and cool stuff. 

He knew how to make a song where a guy could go crazy and improvise, but he also knew how to make tight, orchestrated sections that really highlighted what each musician brought to the table.  Like, he'd craft these sounds that were totally unique and made each piece pop.  He was a master at getting the best out of every player, and that's how he made some of the most awesome jazz ever.

They even say in that big music book, The Grove Music Dictionary, that Ellington was all about using the voice as an instrument, check out his song "Creole Love Call" for that. He was using voices for texture and feeling without all that singing stuff. And in that song, he showed how he could make soloists shine, which he did all the time.

It's a slow blues song, twelve bars, six choruses, each one different. The first chorus is call and response between the voice and the reeds, smooth at first then kinda rough by the end. Chorus two, it's a muted trumpet solo that messes with the melody and throws in some of those bluesy notes. Then chorus three is all clarinet, high and sweet, with the piano adding a little somethin' somethin' underneath. Chorus four is the whole band echoing the first chorus, brass and reeds doin' the call and response thing. Chorus five, this is where it gets wild, the reeds are callin' and respondin' high up, with the brass and rhythm guys doin' this syncopated stop time thing. And the last chorus is back to the first call and response, but this time the voice gets all growl-ey, soloin' like an instrument itself.

Then there's a little tag with the voice doin' some runs and the trombone endin' on this dissonant note, real weird.

Ellington used voice like that in a lot of his stuff, adding this extra layer of sound. 

His song "Hot and Bothered" is another example of how good he was at orchestrating things and finding those cool sounds. He had "Bubber" Miley on trumpet and Baby Cox scatting, and their voices and instruments blended together so well. Then in "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," he used Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton on trombone to start the melody, and it sounded killer.

She'd always felt somethin' was missin'. It was like a hole in her soul, a yearning that just wouldn't quit. This emptiness started creepin' in around 14, right when she was hittin' that teenage groove. Three years later, at 17, it was still there, gnawin' at her. Now, she knew it wasn't some material thing she was after, it was somethin' more...someone. But guys? Forget about it. They'd try their cheesy pick-up lines and awkward dances, but nothin' ever clicked. She'd wrack her brain, tryin' to figure out why this was happenin' to her. Theories flew around, but nothin' stuck. So she just kept livin', always questionin', always searchin'.

Life at home was usually chill. Her folks were good people, peaceful and calm. They rarely argued, and even when she tried to push their buttons, it usually ended in a good-natured debate. Her parents were the picture of serenity, but she, well, she was a whirlwind of energy and fun. It was a good mix, made her pretty darn likeable.

But today? Today was nothin' like usual. She was wanderin' around the house, lookin' for some spark of inspiration, when she heard a yelp from the kitchen. It was her mom's voice, short and sharp. She bolted into the room, panic settin' in, "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?!"  Her mom was sprawled on the floor, lookin' pale and in pain. "Ow...sweetie...need...hospital," her mom gasped, each word a strained effort. "Okay Mom, just tell me where to meet you," she said, her voice shaky but determined. Her mom pointed weakly, and the daughter, thank goodness for those self-defense classes, scooped her up and carried her to the car.

The hospital was a sensory overload - disinfectant, sick smells, and a palpable fear in the air. But she barely noticed. All her energy was focused on gettin' her mom help. She practically flew through the doors, barkin' for a doctor. Concerned faces swarmed around them, a gurney appeared, and they whisked her mom away.  She sat there, waitin', worry gnawin' at her insides.

Turns out, her mom had been tryin' to reach a vase on a high shelf and took a tumble off the step stool.

Listen up, folks! This study was all about how good that Mediterranean Diet (the Med diet) is for your ticker.  They found that the more you stick to it, the less likely you are to get heart problems or have a stroke.  This fancy "aMed" diet is like the Med diet's cooler cousin, with more plants, good fats, and fish, and less of the meaty stuff and bad fats. Think of it like a healthy power-up for your heart!

There's already been some talk about how the Med diet is good for you, but this study focused on strokes and heart attacks specifically. They followed all these nurses for like 20 years and asked them about what they ate. The nurses were awesome and kept track of their meals for years and years. They even double-checked everything with doctors and records to make sure they were getting it right.

So, what did they find? Well, the nurses who ate more like they were on vacation in Greece had way less heart problems and strokes. It's like magic, but it's actually science! The more they ate those healthy foods, the better protected they were.

Whoa, dude, picture this: 2007, the USA goes totally bonkers. Like, everyone's outta work, houses are crashing harder than a video game rage quit, and all the big fancy companies are, like, totally toast. This whole mess is still hanging around, so we gotta figure out what went wrong, right?

So, get this, it all started with some politicians who were, let's just say, not thinking straight. They pushed banks and companies to give out these crazy loans to people who couldn't really afford 'em. It was like handing out candy to a bunch of sugar-crazed kids! And these loans, they weren't even good loans, they were like, "sub-prime" or whatever. 

Meanwhile, these two guys, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, were supposed to be keeping things safe, but they got pressured into bundling up these bad loans into these even weirder things called CDOs and CDSs. It was like a financial game of Jenga, but instead of blocks, they were using people's houses!

When folks started missing payments, BAM! The whole thing came crashing down. Banks ran outta cash, and everyone got dragged down with 'em. It was like a domino effect, except way scarier and with way more money involved. 

This whole mess started way back in 1999, when President Clinton was trying to win another term. He wanted to look good, so he relaxed the rules on lending. That was like pouring gasoline on a fire, except the fire was the economy.

Some smart guy named Steven Holmes even saw it coming back then. He wrote about how Fannie Mae was getting pressured to give out more loans, even though it was risky. He warned that it could lead to another big financial disaster, just like the one with the savings and loans back in the 80s. 

And guess what? He was right!  People started taking out loans they couldn't afford, and they got themselves caught up in all these complicated new types of mortgages. They were buying houses they couldn't really afford, and then they started building stuff on top of stuff, like a financial skyscraper made of wobbly blocks. It was insane!

Then, BOOM! The bubble burst. All those houses that were worth way too much suddenly weren't worth anything. The banks lost tons of money, and some of the biggest companies in the world almost went bankrupt.

It was a total mess. And it's still affecting us today.

Ugh, exposition. That part in your story where you're supposed to show off your writing skills, wowing everyone with your fancy words and captivating sentences. Or maybe the part where your readers yawn, close their tabs, and mutter curses under their breath. I've seen Dr. Merlin yell at her computer screen when she gets stuck in a giant info-dump, and it's not in a good way.

Exposition, my friends, is not your bestie.

You already know the golden rule of writing: "Show, don't tell." But even I, Dr. Merlin, stumble into those boring, wordy paragraphs where nothing happens, or worse, too much happens all at once. Exposition is that little voice whispering in your ear, urging you to get all the background info out of the way before the real fun begins.  (Don't confuse it with the other voice tempting you to spill every single detail about each character's childhood!)

Exposition means dumping a bunch of info on your audience, usually in plain, straightforward language. Think of those long winded scenes in movies where one character drones on and on, giving another character a history lesson, like some kind of real-life "Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In writing, it's the author doing the heavy lifting of the telling.

Let me give you an example. Imagine you're reading a story, and you're told that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, they got hitched in a big fancy wedding, and then, bam! Her husband was murdered right in front of her eyes! Would you really want two whole pages dedicated to explaining all that, with the characters only getting two lines of dialogue each? 

Nah, you'd expect the author to give us a taste of the husband's character, showing us through his words and actions how much he loved his wife. You'd also want to see how the heroine changed and grew because of him, through big gestures and little details.

A good introduction to the husband would make you feel something for him, make you care about his fate. And when he's gone, you'd mourn with the heroine, connecting with her on a deeper level.

In short, you want substance, not just bare bones.

Think of it like this: "They met, they married, he died."  That's the bare minimum. As a writer, you need to give us the juicy details, the "meat on the bones."

Sometimes we're tempted to rush past important stuff. Maybe you have a new character who was in the Air Force, now works the night shift at a gas station, has been married twice, no kids, loves fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the station someday, and just had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

Give us the good stuff!

Mack, why are we even watching the news? This stuff is so boring! The first story was about some dude named Shad Hostettler stabbing his wife in Ashley, Ohio.  Did they even show her face? Nope! Just a picture of Shad lookin' all evil. They said he stabbed her a bunch of times, but that's about it. 

Then they talked about some kid, Travis Buyers, getting shot in Sharon Woods. Sounds pretty rough, but they barely said anything.  It's like they don't care 'cause he's black.  Remember that time a white kid went missing? The whole news was obsessed! 

Next up, some weirdo shot a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter with a .22! They were offering five grand for info on the shooter, so maybe someone will spill the beans.

They gave a quick rundown about the weather, sayin' it's gonna be hot and stormy on Saturday.  Typical.

Then they talked about some dude robbing a UDF. They kept sayin' he was a "dark-skinned black man" wearing a hoodie. What's with all the emphasis on his race? Sounds like someone's trying to stir up some trouble.

Finally, they had a story about this drug kingpin from Texas named Rene Rodriguez.  They kept saying "300 months" instead of 25 years, like that's supposed to sound scarier.  And they mentioned he was Hispanic, which had nothing to do with the story. 

This news is so messed up, I'm outta here!

Brothers, man, they're a crazy bunch. You know how it is, right? It's like, this unbreakable connection, like they're lookin' at each other in the mirror, but seein' even deeper, ya know?  They feel everything together, the good stuff and the bad. Love, pride, jealousy, even that nasty stuff like anger and cruelty - it's all there.

They get each other like nobody else, and sometimes it gets messy. It's like, when things get rough, that bond just shines through, like a crazy light show. But man, it comes with a price, ya know? You gotta deal with all those emotions, the good and the bad. 

See, when you look your brother in the eye, you see yourself, but not how people see you, but like, the real you. It's all in your actions, what you do and the stuff that comes after. That's where you see your true colors, the real deal.

There's this story, "The Scarlet Ibis," about these two brothers, and they're goin' through all this, ya know? It's got this crazy landscape, like a jungle out there, and these two boys are on this trip that's not gonna end well. There's this fightin' going on inside of 'em, pride and disappointment, and it explodes in this big way. Only one brother makes it out alive. The story shows you how those feelings between brothers can be so intense, and the narrator, he's like, right there in the middle of it all, feelin' everything too. 

The main guy in the story, he's all about pride, ya know? From the start, when he and his little brother, Doodle, go out, he's already got this resentment. He wants a brother who can do all this stuff with him, run races, climb trees, be his buddy. But Doodle's got this heart problem, so he's weak and can't do any of that. Imagine that, your dreams crushed right before your eyes! It's messed up. He even thinks about hurting Doodle, can you believe that? But then Doodle smiles at him, and he's like, "Aw, forget it, I love this little guy."

So, get this. Our brains, they're like, totally crazy complex, right? Kinda like trying to figure out a super complicated video game. Back in the day, people thought our brains were like wax tablets or papyrus – kinda like old school notepads. Then they were all, "Nah, it's more like a book!" But now, everyone's like, "Dude, it's like a computer!"

But hold up, these comparisons, they're kinda limited, you know? Like, they can get you thinking some crazy stuff.

See, all this info comes flooding in through our senses. Our eyes see light, our ears hear sounds, our skin feels stuff, and so on. It's all turned into these electrical signals – like, the language of our brain.

And then the brain does this crazy thing. It processes this info, like, a million different ways. It starts with the basics – like, "Hey, there's a black thing on a white thing." Then it's like, "Wait, that black thing looks kinda like a box!" It uses what it already knows to figure stuff out faster. Kinda like using cheats in a game, you know?

But here's the thing – our brains are picky. They only pay attention to the important stuff. Like, you see a ton of grass when you look down, but you don't notice every single blade. But if someone says your name in a crowded room, BAM, you hear it loud and clear.

And then there's memory. Our brains are like, "Ooh, gotta store that!" There's short-term memory – like remembering your last pizza topping – and long-term memory – like remembering your first pet's name. They store stuff in different ways, kinda like different folders on a computer.

But how is all this knowledge organized? There are tons of theories about that, like, maybe it's like a giant web of connections, or maybe it's like a library with books on every topic.

The brain is seriously mind-blowing, man.

Yo, check it! Aldous Huxley's book, "Brave New World," is like, totally a warning about tech and money stuff runnin' wild.  He paints this messed-up future where everyone's all about being part of the crew and gettin' instant happiness, you know? It's like a big, messed up game where people are just pawns,  followin' the rules set by this dude, the World Controller. It's kinda like what Marx woulda said, you dig?  Huxley's got this lowkey suspicion about how these systems are gonna mess things up.  He uses words like "homogeny" and "reification," which are like,  big Communist vibes, to show how messed up it is.

Basically, Huxley's saying capitalism is a scam. They keep us blind to how the rich really get rich, 'cause we're all too busy chasin' our own little pleasures.  It's like brainwashing, man!  The World Controller's like the big boss, makin' everyone crave stuff they don't need.  He's got all the power, and the lower classes are just slaves to the system. They don't even know they're bein' controlled. They're like, "Yeah, this is great! More stuff!" 

And the relationships? Forget about it! There's no real connection between people. They're just empty shells, man.  Huxley's sayin' that technology and money are killin' our soul, makin' us shallow and heartless.  Love?  Emotions?  Nah, not in this world. It's all about lookin' good and havin' a good time, even if it's fake.  It's a total bummer, dude.

Yo, lemme tell ya, gettin' around this crazy place, University Park, is a real pain in the tailfeather! I've been here for like, two and a half years, four and a half semesters, and lemme tell ya, it's a jungle out there! My freshman year, they stuck me in East Halls, man, like, the farthest point east on campus.  Forget the stadium and that Bryce Jordan Center thing, they're still closer to civilization than that!

So, picture this: I gotta trek from my East Halls bunker all the way to Willard, which is like, smack dab in the middle of this campus, just to get to class. On foot, it'd take me 25 minutes, even longer if the weather decides to throw a tantrum, which, let's be real, it does all the time here in State College.

I was talkin' to this dude, a grad not much older than myself, and he spilled the beans:  used to be, East Halls was like, surrounded by a freakin' desert, all empty land. Now? Boom! Sports fields, massive buildings, even a new Creamery and a fancy new health center! And apartments everywhere! This campus keeps growing, but getting around? Getting worse, dude.

So, what's the answer to this mobility mess? Bikes, man! Bikes are the key! But wait, it ain't just about the bike itself. Students gotta ride 'em, and the damn campus needs to play nice with us cyclists.

I was hangin' out with my buddy, he got back on the bike after a few years off. Said he couldn't believe he ever stopped. "Bikes are awesome," he said, "it's like, the only way to get around." They're good for your body, too. Trust me, a bowl of oatmeal and a little pedal power, you'll be cruisin' 30 miles in no time.

Like, most of the students here, I live off campus now. Just as far from the center as some dorms. Best decision I made this year? Bought a bike. Now I got class in Thomas building, a good 25-minute walk from my place. Bike? Five minutes flat if I'm feelin' speedy!

But here's the catch: Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas, but it ain't always a bike-friendly street, you know? Walkin' ain't bad, but I'm too busy for that. No bike, I'm stuck walkin' to class every day. That's like, 30-40 minutes each way, man! Over two and a half hours every week! Forget about it! That's time I don't got.
